{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01B4uhhCjxxZ6S8kiz6mucYj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture:\n\n1. The CA and leaf cert both expire `2026-06-27` (2 days from now, 2026-06-25)\n2. The SANs needed for the leaf cert:\n   - DNS:localhost\n   - DNS:es-http\n   - DNS:es-http.elasticsearch\n   - DNS:es-http.elasticsearch.svc\n   - DNS:es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local\n   - DNS:es-cluster\n   - DNS:es-cluster.elasticsearch\n   - DNS:es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc\n   - DNS:es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local\n   - DNS:es-cluster-0.es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local\n   - DNS:es-cluster-1.es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local\n   - DNS:es-cluster-2.es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local\n\n3. The secret `es-http-tls` is mounted at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/http-certs` in the ES pods, and I have an `openssl-toolbox` pod available to work with\n4. My rotation plan is to generate a new CA with one year validity, then create a new leaf cert signed by it with the same SANs, update both the `es-http-tls` secret and `es-http-ca` configmap, perform a rolling restart of the StatefulSet, and verify HTTPS connectivity afterward\n\nFor distributing the new CA to clients, the `es-http-ca` configmap appears to be the mechanism, so I need to check the Elasticsearch configuration to understand how the certificates are referenced.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4022,"cache_read_input_tokens":46971,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4022},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fb6bd00f-1f2c-48c1-a75e-26e7520afae3","uuid":"39e15107-3d02-44da-a8ef-3e3b76c0aa20","request_id":"req_011CcQ4