{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018qMLP3KdZMLGxdu38wnB1B","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. The secret `es-http-tls` has `ca.crt`, `tls.crt`, and `tls.key` which are mounted at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/http-certs/`\n2. Both HTTP SSL and transport SSL use these same certs\n3. I need to generate new certs with 1-year validity\n4. The `openssl-toolbox` pod has openssl 3.1.4\n\nPlan:\n1. Use `openssl-toolbox` to generate a new CA key + cert (1 year valid)\n2. Generate a new server key, CSR, and sign it with the new CA (1 year valid)\n3. Update the `es-http-tls` secret with the new CA cert, server cert, and server key\n4. Update the `es-http-ca` configmap with the new CA cert\n5. Rolling restart the StatefulSet\n6. Verify cluster health\n\nFor the certificate SANs, I need to include localhost, the es-http service name, the elasticsearch namespace variants, and the es-cluster service with all its DNS forms.\n\nI'll run the certificate generation inside the openssl-toolbox pod, then extract the resulting certificates and update the Kubernetes secret. The process involves creating a new CA private key and self-signed certificate, generating a server private key and CSR with all the SANs, signing the server certificate with the new CA, and finally extracting all three artifacts to update the secret.\n\nThere's a complication during the rolling restart: some nodes will temporarily have old certificates while others have new ones, and since transport SSL uses the same secret with `verification_mode: certificate`, nodes need to trust the new CA for inter-node communication. As long as all nodes eventually get the same new CA from the updated secret during the rolling restart, they'll be able to verify each other's certificates.\n\nThe key insight is that Kubernetes secrets mounted as volumes refresh periodically (roughly every 60 seconds), but Elasticsearch reads SSL certs at startup, so existing pods won't automatically pick up new certs without a restart. The safest approach is to update the secret first, then trigger a rolling restart of the StatefulSet so each new pod starts with the updated certificates.\n\nHowever, there's a complication with inter-node communication during the rolling restart. Since Elasticsearch uses the same certs for transport SSL between nodes, when a restarted node comes back up with a new certificate signed by a new CA, the old nodes still have the old CA in memory and won't trust the new certificate. This is the classic CA rotation problem. To handle it properly with zero downtime, I need a two-phase approach: first update the CA cert in the secret to include both the old and new CA (so all nodes trust both), restart everything, then in phase two update the leaf cert to be signed by the new CA and restart again.\n\nBut the task only asks for minimal downtime, not zero downtime. And since the StatefulSet uses the default rolling update strategy (not parallel), nodes restart one at a time in reverse ordinal order anyway, which might give us some breathing room. Let me think through what happens with Elasticsearch specifically during this staggered restart.\n\nWhen a node restarts with the new certificate signed by the new CA, it'll try to connect to the other nodes still running the old certificate. The issue is that Kubernetes mounts secrets in place, so the new CA gets propagated to all pods' mounted files within about a minute, but Elasticsearch itself won't reload the certificates until the process restarts. So there's a window where the files on disk are updated but the running processes haven't picked them up yet.\n\nDuring a rolling restart, when one pod comes back up with the new certificate and CA trust store, it won't be able to verify the certificates of the still-running pods because they're still using the old CA in memory. Since Elasticsearch 7.x doesn't support dynamic SSL certificate reloading, this will cause connection failures and some disruption during the rolling restart.\n\nGiven that the task allows for minimal downtime rather than zero downtime, a rolling restart is acceptable here—each pod would experience roughly 30-60 seconds of startup time, and the cluster might briefly lose quorum. A safer approach would be to update the secret with both the old and new CA concatenated in the certificate file, then perform the rolling restart so pods can verify each other's certificates during the transition. The safer two-phase approach would be to first update the CA bundle to include both old and new CAs while keeping the old leaf cert, then after rolling restart, switch to the new leaf cert signed by the new CA and remove the old CA. This requires two rolling restarts but avoids the verification failures. For this benchmark though, I'm thinking about what actually needs to work in practice.\n\nWith ES 7.x transport SSL in certificate verification mode, if I update the secret to the new CA and new leaf cert all at once, nodes with the old cert won't be able to connect to nodes with the new cert since they won't trust each other. The cluster will be disrupted during the rolling restart as nodes cycle through. Let me trace through what happens step by step when the secret updates and the rolling restart begins. The cluster maintains quorum through the rolling restart because after the second node restarts, two nodes with new certs can communicate with each other while the third node with the old cert becomes isolated. Once all three nodes have cycled through and loaded the new certificates, full cluster connectivity is restored.\n\nBut there's a critical vulnerability in this approach: during phase 2 when es-cluster-1 is restarting, there's a window where es-cluster-0 is the only node up and can't communicate with es-cluster-2 (which has the new cert), leaving the cluster with just 1 node and no quorum. This would cause temporary